You are working on packages/web/src/Viewport.tsx in a BIM (architectural
  CAD) web app. This task adds visible board-on-board timber cladding geometry
  to wall meshes that carry a 'timber_cladding' material marker.

  CONTEXT
  =======
  The wall element type has an optional field:  materialKey?: string | null

  Walls tagged with materialKey === 'timber_cladding' should render with
  vertical cladding boards as child geometry proud of their outer face.

  makeWallMesh (find it in the file) builds a THREE.Mesh from
  BoxGeometry(len, height, thick). It currently ends:
    mesh.position.set(sx + dx / 2, elevM + height / 2, sz + dz / 2);
    mesh.rotation.y = Math.atan2(dz, dx);
    mesh.userData.bimPickId = wall.id;
    addEdges(mesh);
    return mesh;

  makeWallWithOpenings (also in the file) builds a CSG-subtracted wall and
  ends its try block:
    const mesh = new THREE.Mesh(wallBrush.geometry, wallMat);
    mesh.position.set(wcx, wcy, wcz);
    mesh.rotation.y = yaw;
    mesh.userData.bimPickId = wall.id;
    addEdges(mesh);
    return mesh;

  In both functions the local variables `len`, `height`, and `thick` are
  already in scope. Neither function takes a selectedId parameter.

  The BoxGeometry axes are: X = along wall length, Y = up, Z = wall thickness.
  The outer face is the +Z face at local z = +thick/2.

  The file already has top-level helpers addEdges(mesh) and
  readToken(name, fallback) — no imports needed for those.

  TASK
  ====
